<div class="main">

<div class="section" id="intro">
<h1><i class="fas fa-radiation"></i> Chernobyl: Reaction & Reform</h1>
<p>On April 26, 1986, Reactor 4 at the <strong>Chernobyl Nuclear Power Plant</strong> exploded in Ukraine. Its RBMK design had serious safety flaws. Radiation spread across Europe, forcing the evacuation of Pripyat. The Soviet Union initially tried to hide the disaster, showing how politics can worsen crises (“Report on the Accident at the Chernobyl Nuclear Power Station”).</p>
<p><strong>Thesis:</strong> Chernobyl caused fear worldwide, sparked immediate reactions, and led to reforms in nuclear safety, international law, and reactor design, showing how disasters drive change.</p>
</div>

<div class="section" id="history">
<h2><i class="fas fa-history"></i> History & Cover-Up</h2>
<p>The explosion occurred during a poorly planned safety test. Human error and flawed reactor design caused overheating. Radiation was detected in Sweden before the Soviet Union admitted the accident. This exposed flaws in Soviet politics and prompted global concern (“Chernobyl Explosion”).</p>
<p>The 1979 <strong>Three Mile Island</strong> accident in the U.S. had already shown the need for better training and emergency planning, but Chernobyl forced worldwide action (“Report on the Accident at the Chernobyl Nuclear Power Station”).</p>
<img src="images/chernobyl_shelter.png" alt="Chernobyl Shelter">
</div>

<div class="section" id="safety">
<h2><i class="fas fa-shield-alt"></i> Safety Improvements Over Time</h2>
<h3>After Chernobyl</h3>
<ul>
<li>RBMK reactors redesigned to prevent overheating (“RBMK Reactors – Appendix”).</li>
<li>IAEA strengthened international safety rules (“How Chernobyl Jump-Started the Global Nuclear Safety Regime”).</li>
</ul>
<h3>After Fukushima, Japan (2011)</h3>
<ul>
<li>Backup cooling systems improved.</li>
<li>Stronger sea walls and flood protections added.</li>
<li>Automatic shutdown systems became mandatory.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Modern Designs</h3>
<p><strong>China:</strong> Hualong One reactors with double containment and passive cooling (“Plans For New Reactors Worldwide”).</p>
<p><strong>France:</strong> European Pressurized Reactors (Generation III+) with automatic shutdown systems. Modern reactors are safer and more efficient than older designs.</p>
</div>

<div class="section" id="nuclear-power">
<h2><i class="fas fa-atom"></i> Nuclear Power Worldwide</h2>
<p>Countries like France, China, and the U.S. rely on nuclear power. Nuclear energy grew in the 1970s and 1980s, slowed after Chernobyl, and increased again after 2000.</p>

<h3>Map of Nuclear Plants</h3>
<iframe src="https://www.world-nuclear.org/information-library/current-and-future-generation/plans-for-new-reactors-worldwide.aspx"></iframe>

